{"key":"post-9857991","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9857991</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; How do you know when your LC is dead?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You don't.&amp;nbsp; This is why I recommend against making LC from spores.&amp;nbsp; You never know if it's healthy or contaminated until you use it, thus all that time it's spent growing slower than any other medium is wasted.&amp;nbsp; If you transfer contaminated or weak mycelium from one LC to another, you simply spread the problem.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you want to expand mycelium fast, learn to proof your cultures on agar, and then take them to sterilized grains.&amp;nbsp; It will be much faster and you'll always know what you have.&amp;nbsp; If you need LC at that point, you can always add sterilized water to the jar of colonized grains, shake it up, and then draw the water back out.&amp;nbsp; This will give you myceliated water at least 100 times faster than growing from spores in a sugar or honey water mix.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9858190</next>\n<prev>9857952</prev>\n<first>9857522</first>\n<last>9858231</last>\n<when>1235524122</when>\n<utime>02/25/09 03:08 AM</utime>\n</post>"}